Preheat your oven to 200°C. Remove the @unsalted butter{30%g} and @21 day aged British sirloin steaks{2} from the fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Pick the @rosemary{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Chop the @potatoes{450%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips (no need to peel). Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and half the rosemary, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Peel the @garlic cloves{2}. Pop half into a small piece of #foil{} with a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and scrunch to enclose it. When the oven is hot, roast the potatoes on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn the potatoes halfway through. Add the garlic parcel to the tray for ~{10-12%minutes} of cooking time then remove. Meanwhile, grate the remaining garlic (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @green beans{150%g}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the grated garlic, turn the heat down to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}. Then add a splash of @water{splash} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some foil. Allow to cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Then transfer to a #bowl{} and cover to keep warm.

Once the garlic has roasted, remove from the foil and mash with a #fork{}. Pop into a small bowl with the butter and remaining rosemary. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then mix to combine and set aside.

Pop the (now empty) frying pan back on high heat with a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}. Season the steaks with @salt{} and @pepper{}. When the oil is hot, lay them in the pan and fry until browned, ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want them medium rare.

> TIP: Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more cooked.

Once cooked, transfer the steaks to a #plate{}. Spoon over the butter, cover with foil and allow to rest for a couple of minutes.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat. The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Thinly slice the steak, then plate up with the potatoes and garlicky green beans alongside. Drizzle any buttery juices over the steak. Enjoy!